The paper deals with distributed statistical estimation, which involves splitting a large data set across multiple machines with limited communication between them. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category, which deals with the transmission, processing, and storage of information. Additionally, the paper studies refinements of the classical minimax risk that apply to distributed settings, which suggests that it could also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category, which deals with the design and analysis of algorithms that can learn from data. The paper also establishes lower bounds for a variety of problems, including location estimation and parameter estimation, which suggests that it could belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category, which deals with the design and analysis of algorithms and data structures. Furthermore, the paper studies distributed protocols that involve independent message passing and interactive communication, which suggests that it could belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category, which deals with the analysis and design of systems that interact with their environment. Finally, the paper introduces a novel class of quantitative data-processing inequalities, which suggests that it could also belong to the Mathematical Analysis (cs.MA) sub-category, which deals with the study of mathematical concepts and techniques that are relevant to computer science.
